{
  "text": "The changes in the signal amplitude are more precisely seen in the difference spectra (compare figure 4(a) ) relative to T = 0 fs. For DS \u03b1 a weaker decrease of signal amplitude compared to DS \u03b2 can be observed, which confirms the different dynamics already seen in transient absorption and the higher stability of |\u03b1 . Comparing the difference spectra for T = 50 and 250 fs, a progressive decrease to lower wavenumbers of the combined SE and GSB signal can be observed. At T = 0 the signal consists of GSB and SE contributions. After a given population time (T = 50 fs) the signal shifts to lower wavenumbers as the SE contribution is influenced by a Stokes shift. As the lifetime in the Soret band is \u2248 150 fs [CITATION_1] the Stokes-shifted SE vanishes for T 150 fs while the GSB is still maintained, leading to the observed stronger signal decrease at lower wavenumbers. The most important additional feature is an increasing signal amplitude for DS \u03b2 at wavenumbers corresponding to the lower energetic state |\u03b1 , which is a consequence of a coupling between |\u03b2 and |\u03b1 . This signal is indicative of relaxation from |\u03b2 into |\u03b1 since molecules excited into |\u03b2 now show absorption at frequencies corresponding to the state |\u03b1 while at the same time the SE signal for |\u03b2 decreases.",
  "correct_citation": {
